red environments depends on evolution and adaptation across life’s network.Difficult times lie ahead for many of Earth’s species as climates and habitats transform. At the same time, new and altered life-forms are arising and spreading in association with human activities. We are also learning to reshape and create life by mimicking the mechanisms of horizontal evolution, and we are coevolving with technology as we enhance our bodies, brains, and life spans. The Network of Life shows why and how increasing our knowledge of horizontal evolution can provide critical lessons as we navigate our looming challenges.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Evolution.2bisacsh  aDavid P. Mindell.  aEvolution’s New Narrative: Why It Matters and What It Tells Us.  aarchaea viruses.  abacteria.  abiodiversity.  adecentralization genomics.  aendosymbioses.  aenvironmental health.  aevolution.  aevolutionary biology.  afungi.  afuture humans.  ahorizontal gene transfer.  ahuman health.  ahybridization animals.  amolecular evolution.  aphylogeny.  aplants.  atree of life.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311074975540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978069122876140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691228761423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691228761/original  a978-3-11-074975-5  Princeton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles